# Rule: Entity Invariants via Value Objects

For DDD entities, do not validate primitive input directly inside entity methods when a dedicated Value Object can represent that concept.

- Put business validation and normalization rules in Value Objects (e.g. `Name`, `Title`, `Email`, `Money`).
- Entity properties should prefer Value Object types over raw primitives for domain concepts.
- Entity methods should accept Value Objects (or create them at the application boundary), not duplicate validation logic.
- Avoid repeated checks like `string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(...)` across entities; centralize them in the related Value Object.
- Keep entities focused on behavior and state transitions, not low-level primitive validation details.

## Example

```csharp
// ✅ Value Object owns validation
public sealed class ValueObjectName
{
    public string Value { get; }

    public ValueObjectName(string value)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(value))
            throw new ArgumentException("Value is required.");

        Value = value.Trim();
    }
}

// ✅ Entity uses Value Object
public class EntityName
{
    public int Id { get; private set; }
    public ValueObjectName Name { get; private set; } = null!;

    public void UpdateName(ValueObjectName name) => Name = name;
}
```
